{{lang: TypeScript}}

# Wefts

`Weft` defines the line-level AST nodes. Each weft is one source line, typed by the mode it sits in and the tokens found on it. Wefts are health-bearing `loomNode`s, so they carry `type`, `position`, and `health` like any node. A weft's position spans exactly one line. `LoomWeft`, the union of them all, is the element the tokeniser streams between passes.

## The heading weft

A `HeadingWeft` is a `#`-heading line. Its `headingStart` records the level for the reader; `title` is the optional trimmed text after the marker; `tag` and `specifier` are optional â€” the tokeniser synthesises a hash `tag` for a tagless heading, and a heading with no specifier inherits the document's language. The classifier emits the weft with incomplete placeholders for the subtokens it has not recognised, and the tokeniser settles them.

=>

export const HeadingWeftSchema = loomNode('HeadingWeft', {
  headingStart: HeadingStartTokenSchema,
  title: Schema.optional(HeadingTitleTokenSchema),
  tag: Schema.optional(TagTokenSchema),
  specifier: Schema.optional(
    Schema.Union(SpecifierTokenSchema, PathSpecifierTokenSchema),
  ),
})
export type HeadingWeft = typeof HeadingWeftSchema.Type

## The body wefts

The five body wefts are the lines inside a section. An `ArrowWeft` is the `=>` line that opens code, carrying any inline `code` and the `::[â€¦]` anchors in it. A `TildeWeft` is the `~` line that opens prose, carrying any inline `prose`. A `PreambleWeft` is a default-mode line before any transition, carrying the `::[â€¦]` warp declarations on it. A `ProseWeft` is a line in prose mode, opaque to Loom. A `CodeWeft` is a line in code mode â€” opaque too, but its `::[â€¦]` anchors are recognised.

=>

export const ArrowWeftSchema = loomNode('ArrowWeft', {
  arrow: ArrowTokenSchema,
  code: Schema.optional(CodeTokenSchema),
  anchors: Schema.Array(WarpAnchorTokenSchema),
})
export type ArrowWeft = typeof ArrowWeftSchema.Type

export const TildeWeftSchema = loomNode('TildeWeft', {
  tilde: TildeTokenSchema,
  prose: Schema.optional(ProseTokenSchema),
})
export type TildeWeft = typeof TildeWeftSchema.Type

export const PreambleWeftSchema = loomNode('PreambleWeft', {
  warps: Schema.Array(WarpTokenSchema),
})
export type PreambleWeft = typeof PreambleWeftSchema.Type

export const ProseWeftSchema = loomNode('ProseWeft', {})
export type ProseWeft = typeof ProseWeftSchema.Type

export const CodeWeftSchema = loomNode('CodeWeft', {
  anchors: Schema.Array(WarpAnchorTokenSchema),
})
export type CodeWeft = typeof CodeWeftSchema.Type

## The weft unions

`LoomWeft` is the union of every weft kind â€” the tokeniser's stream element. `SectionBodyWeft` is the narrower union the grammar admits inside a section body: arrow, code, tilde, and prose, in the forward-only order the classifier enforces.

=>

export const LoomWeftSchema = Schema.Union(
  HeadingWeftSchema,
  ArrowWeftSchema,
  TildeWeftSchema,
  PreambleWeftSchema,
  ProseWeftSchema,
  CodeWeftSchema,
)
export type LoomWeft = typeof LoomWeftSchema.Type

export const SectionBodyWeftSchema = Schema.Union(
  ArrowWeftSchema,
  CodeWeftSchema,
  TildeWeftSchema,
  ProseWeftSchema,
)
export type SectionBodyWeft = typeof SectionBodyWeftSchema.Type

## What this module draws on

Each weft is a `loomNode` built from Effect's `Schema`; its subtokens are the heading, arrow, tilde, code, prose, specifier, tag, warp, and anchor schemas from `LoomTokens`.

=>

import { Schema } from 'effect'
import { loomNode } from './LoomNode'
import {
  ArrowTokenSchema,
  CodeTokenSchema,
  HeadingStartTokenSchema,
  PathSpecifierTokenSchema,
  ProseTokenSchema,
  HeadingTitleTokenSchema,
  SpecifierTokenSchema,
  TagTokenSchema,
  TildeTokenSchema,
  WarpAnchorTokenSchema,
  WarpTokenSchema,
} from './LoomTokens'

